      "processed_at": "2026-04-09 00:18:14.696400",
      "extracted_content": "MGMT 3130\nJudgment and Decision Making in Organizations\nUnit 2.6\nPlanning Fallacy\n1\n\nWhere are we now?\nPart 1: Part 2: Common Traps of Part 3: JDM Issues in\nDecision Analysis Human Irrationality Contemporary\nOrganizations\nUnit 2.1\nTwo systems of Unit 2.5\nthinking Prospect theory\nUnit 2.2\nUnit 2.6 Presentation day 1:\nAvailability heuristic\nPlanning fallacy Unethical behavior\nUnit 1.1 Unit 2.3\nUnit 2.7\nDefining your decision Representativeness Presentation day 2:\nEscalation of\nproblems heuristic Going green\ncommitment\nUnit 1.2\nUnit 2.4\nUnit 2.8\nDecisions involving Presentation day 3:\nBounded awareness\nTemporal decision\nmultiple objectives Diversity and inclusion\nmaking\nUnit 1.3\nUnit 2.9\nDecision making under Presentation day 4:\nBiases in group\nuncertainty Performance appraisal\ndecision making\n2\n\nUnit 2.6 Planning Fallacy\n• What’s planning fallacy?\n• Mechanisms underlying planning fallacy\n• The inside–outside model (neglect of past experiences +\nnarrow focus on plans for successful task completion)\n• Conjunctive-events and disjunctive-events bias\n• Debiasing strategies for planning fallacy\n3\n\nPLANNING FALLACY\n• Consider the following classic example of planning fallacy:\nIn 1976, Daniel Kahneman was involved in a project to develop a curriculum for\na new subject area for high schools in Israel. In a meeting, individual team\nmembers’ estimation on completion time ranged from 18 to 30 months.\nTry to recall as many curriculum development\nNot all the teams that I can think of have\nteams as you can. Think of them as they were in a\ncompleted their task. About 40% of them\nstage comparable to ours at present. How long did\neventually gave up. Of the remaining,\nit take them at that point to reach completion?\ncompletion time ranged from 7 to 10 years.\nAny reasons to believe that our\nNo. Indeed, my impression is that\nteam is more skilled in curriculum\nwe are slightly below average in\ndevelopment than the earlier ones?\nterms of resources and potential.\nA distinguished expert in curriculum development\n4\n\n• Planning fallacy is the tendency to underestimate the resources (time and\nmoney) needed for project completion, despite that the vast majority of similar\nprojects have failed to proceed as planned.\n• Planning fallacy has the following features:\nOptimism about\nthe future\nPessimistic past\nTime\nexperience\n5\n\nExamples of planning fallacy:\nThe average time overrun of IT projects Students have ample experiences\nin U.S. was 222% . finishing their assignments later than\n(The Standish Group, 1995)\noriginally planned.\nTime Time\nManagers of IT projects continue to be They still submit their thesis, on average,\ntoo optimistic about their own project. 28 days longer than they had anticipated\n.\n(Buehler, Griffin & Ross, 1994, Study 1)\nTime and cost overruns have been\nYour turn:\ncharacteristics of public infrastructure\nprojects.\nTime\nExecutives continue to be too optimistic\nabout their new infrastructure projects.\n6\n\nMECHANISMS UNDERLYING THE PLANNING FALLACY\nWhen predicting task completion, we should derive our predictions from both\n(i) singular information – aspects of the particular task at hand, and\n(ii) distributional information – the distribution of outcomes for similar tasks, e.g.,\nyour own past experiences (personal distributional information) or past\nexperiences of others (populational distributional information).\nFactors that prevent us from generating an accurate prediction:\n• The inside–outside model (neglect of past experiences + narrow focus on plans\nfor successful task completion)\n• Conjunctive-events and disjunctive-events bias\n7\n\nThe Inside–Outside Model\nThe inside–outside model of planning fallacy claims that people rely far more on\nsingular information (inside view) than on distributional information (outside\nview) when estimating the completion time / resources needed of a task.\nPeople tend to generate their predictions by considering the unique features of\nthe task at hand and constructing a scenario of their successful task completion,\ni.e., to develop a series of steps that will lead from the beginning to a successful\nconclusion of the project. Doing so results in reduced attention to past experience\nand future impediments.\nLet’s examine:\n1. Why people fail to incorporate past experience (distributional information) in\ntheir completion estimates?\n2. Why the resulting focus on singular information is dominated by plans for\nsuccessful task completion (vs. obstacles)?\n8\n\nDespite the predictive value of past experience (distributional information),\nwe neglect them while forming prediction. Why might this be so?\n1. The forward nature of prediction: The act of prediction, by its very nature,\nelicits a focus on the future rather than on the past; a future orientation may\nprevent individuals from looking backward in time.\n2. Attributional processes that diminish the relevance of past failures to the\npresent: To the extent that people perceive a previous failure to be caused\nby external, unstable, and specific factors, they need not connect the past\nfailure to future occasions.\n9\n\nConsider the following study (in which think-aloud procedure was used):\n• First, participants (UG students) described a school project that they planned to\ncomplete in the next 2 weeks and its deadline. Then were asked to (i) predict as\naccurately as possible when they would finish the project, and (ii) indicate how\ncertain they were about the predicted time.\n• Second, participants were asked to recall (i) one occasion in which they had failed\nto complete a task by the time they originally predicted and a similar prediction\nfailure experienced by a friend or acquaintance, then (ii) explain why each of the\ntwo tasks was not finished by the expected time.\n• Participants were interviewed 1 week after the project deadline to record the\nactual completion time.\nPredicted completion date Verbal protocols on\nActual\n+ Verbal protocols on attribution about (i) own\ncompletion\nprediction + Confidence prediction failure &\ndate\nratings on prediction (ii) others’ prediction failure\n10\n\n• Results:\nPredicted vs. actual completion times:\nOn average, participants reported they were 83.5% certain that they would\ncomplete the project in the predicted time. But only 43.6% of the participants\nfinished their projects within the predicted time.\nVerbal protocols on prediction:\nA 7-category system was developed to characterize the content of participants’\nverbal protocols as they generated their prediction. For each participant, the\nproportion of responses assigned to each category was calculated. (Please see next\nslide for information on those categories.)\nConsistent with the inside–outside model, participants (i) focused more on future\nscenarios than past experiences, and (ii) thought more about plans for future\nprogress than potential impediments.\n11\n\nCategory Proportion Example\nFuture plans: Participants’ plans for .71 \"Let's see, I have the morning off, I have classes in the\ncompleting a project and thoughts about afternoon, I have to do some fieldwork in the late\nits likely progression. afternoon, so it will probably be done about 7pm.\"\nFuture problems: Participants’ .03 \"I don't know. It might take a bit longer because I'm not\nreferences to potential impediments. quite caught up in this.\"\nPast success: References to projects that .06 \"I'll put about five hours, that's about my average for all\nwere completed as anticipated. of the assignments.\"\nPast problems: References to problems .01 \"It took me days and days and days to do a term paper\nor impediments encountered in the past. last year for Social Work.\"\nOthers’ experience: References to other .01 \"I think it's more time than most people are spending\npeople's experiences. on it, but I have to weigh all of the information given to\nme in this project.\"\nDisposition: Participants’ personal .02 \"I'm very slow and I'm a perfectionist, especially as far\ncharacteristics. as art is concerned.\"\nDeadline .15 \"Well, the due date is July 12 at 5 o'clock. I'll probably\nfinish the project half an hour before it's due.\"\n12\n\nVerbal protocols on attribution:\nA set of 7-point scales was developed to rate the attributions along 3 dimensions:\nThe extent to which the cause (i) implicated other people and circumstances or the\nperson themselves (external vs. internal), (ii) was temporary or persistent\n(transitory vs. stable), and (iii) was specific to the particular project or relevant to\nmany different activities (specific vs. global).\nComparing to attributions offered for others’ prediction failures, participants’\nattributions for their own prediction failures were more external, transitory, and\nspecific (e.g., “my delay was an accident” vs. “my friend failed to get the work done\nas predicted because he is a procrastinator”), i.e., participants made use of\nattributional mechanisms to discount the relevance of past failures.\nBuehler, R., Griffin, D., & Ross, M. (1994). Exploring the ‘‘planning fallacy’’: Why people underestimate their task completion\ntimes. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 67, 366–381. Study 3.\n13\n\nWhy is the inside view (singular information) dominated by plans for\nsuccessful task completion (vs. possible obstacles or interruptions)?\nMotivated reasoning is a form of reasoning in which people construct arguments\nin a biased fashion to arrive at a preferred conclusion (i.e., a conclusion that\npeople are motivated to draw).\nIn the domain of planning, our goal / motivation to finish tasks quickly enhances\nthe accessibility of information that is consistent with the desired goal, this leads\nto a greater focus on successful future plans and a reduced focus on potential\nobstacles.\n14\n\nConsider a study on the role of motivated reasoning in planning fallacy:\n• Participants were asked to complete a series of word puzzle tasks:\n1st word 2nd word Manipulation 3rd word\npuzzle task puzzle task of motivation puzzle task\nTime\n• After the first two tasks were completed, the motivation manipulation were\nintroduced:\nSpeed incentive condition: US$2 reward for finishing 1 min faster than the\nprevious tasks and US$4 reward for finishing 2 mins faster.\nNo incentive condition: Simply being told to finish as quickly as possible.\n• Participants then (i) predicted how long it would take to complete the 3rd task,\n(ii) wrote down thoughts that came through their minds when making the\nprediction, and (iii) completed the 3rd task.\n15\n\n• Results:\nPredicted vs. actual completion times:\nParticipants in the speed incentive (vs.\nno incentive) condition predicted shorter\ncompletion times, i.e., suffered more from\nplanning fallacy.\nVerbal protocols on prediction:\nA 4-category system was developed to\ncharacterize the content of participants’ verbal\nprotocols.\n- Using past: Using past tasks as the basis for\npredicting their completion time (e.g., “My first\ntime was longer than the second, so I chose a\ntime half way between them”).\n16\n\n- Discounting past: Considered the past tasks but explained why the upcoming task\nwould be different from the previous ones (e.g., “I looked at my last time score but\ndecided that I would probably do better because of practice”).\n- Future planning: Plans and strategies for completing the upcoming task (e.g., “Next\ntime I’ll look for letter E”).\n- Future impediments: Problems or impediments that might be encountered with the\nupcoming task (e.g., “The next set of words might be more difficult”).\nParticipants in the speed incentive (vs. no incentive) condition generated\n(i) fewer thoughts about using the past as a basis for prediction, (ii) more thoughts\ndesigned to deny the relevance of the past tasks, (iii) more thoughts about future\nplans or strategies, and (iv) fewer thoughts about potential problems.\nBuehler, R., Griffin, D., & MacDonald, H. (1997). The role of motivated reasoning in optimistic time predictions. Personality and\nSocial Psychology Bulletin, 23(3), 238-247. Study 2.\n17\n\nConjunctive-events and Disjunctive-events Bias\nConjunctive-events bias: People tend to\noverestimate the probability of conjunctive\nevents (the “AND events”).\nE.g., You are trying to catch Flight 1, which Flight 1\nFlight 2\nyou have 30% chance of getting on it, and\na connecting Flight 2, which you have 30%\nchance of getting on it. What is the\nprobability of making both flights?\n• While people anchor their predictions The probability of the intersection is\ntoo high (near 30%), the actual likelihood the product of the components:\nof making both flights is 9%. p(F1 AND F2) = p(F1)*p(F2)\n18\n\nDisjunctive-events bias: People tend to\nunderestimate the probability of disjunctive\nevents (the “OR events”).\nFlight 1\nE.g., You can take either Flight 1 (which\nFlight 2\nyou have 30% chance of getting on it), or\nFlight 2 (which you also have 30% chance\nof getting on it). What is the probability\nthat you can make the trip?\n• While people anchor their predictions p(F1 OR F2)\n= p(F1) + p(F2) - p(F1 AND F2)\ntoo low (near 30%), the actual likelihood\n= p(F1) + p(F2) - p(F1)*p(F2)\nof making a flight is 51%.\n19\n\nConjunctive-events and disjunctive-events bias offers an explanation for planning\nfallacy: When constructing future scenarios of multifaceted projects, we tend to\nunderestimate the likelihood that our plans might go wrong.\n• E.g., A building can only be completed on time if there are no delays in the\ndelivery of materials, no strikes, no shortages of funds during construction, no\nunusual weather conditions, and so on. Although any one of these setbacks\nmay be unlikely, the probability of at least one of these setbacks occurring is\nconsiderably more so.\n20\n\nDEBIASING THE PLANNING FALLACY\nDiscussion:\nLet’s suppose you’re a programmer, and you’re developing a computer game. To\ncomplete the game development, you have to design a mockup, complete the\nmain scene (play button, help button), game scene (score display, sound effects, object\nmovement), win scene (“you win”, fireworks animation), lose scene (“game over”, restart\nbutton), help scene (text, back button).\nYour boss asked you to estimate when the computer game will be ready so that\nhe can announce the product launch date accordingly.\nGiven the mechanisms of planning fallacy (e.g., neglect of past experiences,\nnarrow focus on plans for successful task completion, conjunctive-events and\ndisjunctive-events bias), what can you / your boss do to reduce planning fallacy\n(and thus the negative consequences associated with it)?\n21\n\nLet’s examine some examples of debiasing strategies:\n1. Use past distributions as the basis for prediction.\n• To reduce planning fallacy, decision makers should base their prediction on\nactual performance in a reference class of comparable projects (distributional\ninformation) – Reference class forecasting.\n• E.g., In a software company, programmers were significantly underestimating\nthe amount of time it would take them to complete various tasks, leading to\nmissed deadlines and burnout. Rather than trying to change the\nprogrammers’ estimates, the company accommodated the planning fallacy by\nadding “buffer time” to projects. The company looked at historical data on\nwork completion dates to determine how much buffer time to add to each\nproject, such as 20% for a minor software update or 40% for a more complex\noperating system update.\n22\n\n2. Use unpacking to reveal the complexity (potential impediments) of the task.\nConsider an experiment:\n• Participants were given 9 unformatted text (9 definitions adapted from a\ndictionary), and were asked to edit the text using MS Word so that it looked\nexactly like the properly formatted version.\n• Participants were asked to unpack the task into subcomponents, i.e., to list\neach and every specific step that would be needed in order to complete the\nformatting task such as “adding italics”, “adding punctuation”, and “capitalizing\nletters”.\nKruger, J., & Evans, M. (2004). If you don't want to be late, enumerate: Unpacking reduces the planning fallacy. Journal of\nExperimental Social Psychology, 40(5), 586-598. Studies 3 and 5.\n23\n\n• 2 experimental conditions:\nPacked\nTime prediction Unpack the task Complete the task\ncondition\nUnpacked\nUnpack the task Time prediction Complete the task\ncondition\n• Results:\nMean predicted and actual Unpacking a whole project into\nformatting completion times (mins) subcomponents resulted in less optimistic\n50 predictions. The subtasks serve as reminders\nPredicted Actual\nof steps that need to be completed, but\n40\nwould have otherwise been unattended in\n30 the rosy future scenarios.\n20 Further study showed that the influence of\nunpacking is greater for complex task than\n10\nfor simple task.\nPacked Unpacked\n24\n\nIntended Learning Outcomes For Unit 2.6 Time For Reflection\nRecall an experience in which\nBy now, you should be able to:\nyou’ve exhibited planning\n• Define planning fallacy, and discuss its impacts in\nfallacy. How would you\norganizational context and in your personal life.\nprevent it from happening\n• Describe the mechanisms underlying planning fallacy,\nagain in the future?\nand then suggest ways to debias.\n25",
