      "uploaded_at": "2026-04-10 13:52:46.189007",
      "processed_at": "2026-04-10 13:52:47.638103",
      "extracted_content": "MGMT 3130\nJudgment and Decision Making in Organizations\nUnit 2.7\nEscalation of Commitment\n1\n\nWhere are we now?\nPart 1: Part 2: Common Traps of Part 3: JDM Issues in\nDecision Analysis Human Irrationality Contemporary\nOrganizations\nUnit 2.1\nTwo systems of Unit 2.5\nthinking Prospect theory\nUnit 2.2\nUnit 2.6 Presentation day 1:\nAvailability heuristic\nPlanning fallacy Unethical behavior\nUnit 1.1 Unit 2.3\nUnit 2.7\nDefining your decision Representativeness Presentation day 2:\nEscalation of\nproblems heuristic Going green\ncommitment\nUnit 1.2\nUnit 2.4\nUnit 2.8\nDecisions involving Presentation day 3:\nBounded awareness\nTemporal decision\nmultiple objectives Diversity and inclusion\nmaking\nUnit 1.3\nUnit 2.9\nDecision making under Presentation day 4:\nBiases in group\nuncertainty Performance appraisal\ndecision making\n2\n\nUnit 2.7 Escalation of Commitment\n• What’s the escalation of commitment?\n• Mechanisms underlying the escalation of commitment\n• The expectancy explanation\n• Sunk cost fallacy\n• Goal substitution effect\n• Self-justification theory\n• Self-presentation theory\n• Psychological ownership and confirmation bias\n• Debiasing strategies for the escalation of commitment\n3\n\nESCALATION OF COMMITMENT\nEscalation of commitment happens when decision makers continue to dedicate\nresources (e.g., time and money) to a failing course of action.\n• Escalation of commitment has the following features:\nNegative feedback about the\npreviously chosen option\nTime\nPrevious decision Subsequent decision to\nwith sunk cost persist with the previously\nchosen option\n4\n\nExamples of the escalation of commitment:\nFound himself not interested\nin being a dentist\nStock price dropped\nTime\nTime\nBought a Started a\nGraduated and got a\nBought more of the\nstock dental degree\ndissatisfying dentist job\nstock at low price\nYour turn:\nSpent a lot of $$ but\nno R&D achievement\nTime\nA company started\nInvested even\na R&D project more $$\n5\n\nMECHANISMS UNDERLYING THE ESCALATION OF COMMITMENT\nSometimes it makes sense to persist in face of negative feedback (i.e., it’s rational):\n• The expectancy explanation\nSometimes the decision to escalate our commitment is based on irrational thoughts:\n• Sunk cost fallacy\n• Goal substitution effect\n• Self-justification theory\n• Self-presentation theory\n• Psychological ownership and confirmation bias\n6\n\nThe Expectancy Explanation\nThe expectancy explanation: Decision makers exhibit greater escalation tendency\nwhen the expected value of persistence (vs. withdrawal) is larger, e.g.,\n When the value of goal attainment is higher\n When the probability of goal attainment is higher\nConsider the following study:\n• Participants were asked to play the role of an assistant director of the World\nBank, and to choose among 3 potential locations for developing an industrial\ncomplex in Kenya.\n• 1st decision was made by participants.\n• Negative feedback: $70 million of the original allocation of $80 million had been\nspent for the project, yet the industrial complex was only 50% completed.\nStaw, B.M., & Ross, J. (1978). Commitment to a policy decision: A multi-theoretical perspective. Administrative Science Quarterly,\n23(1), 40-64.\n7\n\n• Two experimental conditions:\nTemporary setback condition: Enduring setback condition:\nHighly unusual amount of rain The slow progress was caused by\nthroughout the region was responsible enduring setback. There was corruption\nfor the delay in the project but it was in the area and that raw materials for\nunlikely to constitute a recurring setback. the project had been diverted.\n• All participants made a 2nd decision: “An additional $70 million has been made\navailable to the World Bank. How much additional funding ($0-70M) do you\nwish to allocate to this Kenya project?”\nNegative feedback on the prior decision\n• Results:\n(with the nature-of-setback manipulation)\nParticipants invested more into the Kenya\nproject when the setback is of temporary\n(vs. enduring) nature [i.e., when the Time\nprobability of goal attainment is higher].\nParticipants Participants indicated\nmade a decision their escalation tendency\n8\n\nSunk Cost Fallacy\nA demonstration\n Scenario 1: Imagine that you paid HK$100 for a ticket to see a horror movie.\nHalfway through the movie you realize the movie is extremely boring, and all\nthe scenes look very fake. How likely you will now walk out of the movie theater?\n Scenario 2: Imagine that you received a free ticket (which is worth HK$100) to\nsee a horror movie. Halfway through the movie you realize the movie is\nextremely boring, and all the scenes look very fake. How likely you will now walk\nout of the movie theater?\n• Results:\nMean likelihood to If you close the account\nleave halfway You paid now, the account balance\nthrough the movie* will be…\nScenario 1 $100 Negative, “in RED”\nScenario 2 Nothing Zero\n* Scale: 0 (not at all likely) <--------> 10 (extremely likely)\nResults of MGMT 3130 in-class activity\n9\n\nIn the previous case, the money used to purchase the movie ticket is a sunk cost –\na cost that was incurred in the past and cannot be recovered once spent.\nRationally (from standard economics sense), sunk costs should be ignored when\nmaking decisions about future investment. All that matters should be future costs\nand benefits.\nIn the previous case, what should you consider?\n• The enjoyment you get from doing something else if you walk out of the movie\ntheater.\n• The enjoyment (or disappointment) of watching the rest of the movie.\n• Not the sunk cost!\nIn the context of the escalation of commitment, decision makers are unwilling to\nwithdraw from the failing course of action because they are unwilling to accept the\npreviously committed resources as a loss (closing an account “in red” is extremely\npainful).\n10\n\nConsider an experiment:\nCondition 1: Condition 2:\nAs the president of an airline company, As the president of an airline company,\nyou have spent $9 million into the R&D you have to decide whether or not to\nof a radar-blank plane. Now you find invest $1 million into a R&D project –\nthat another firm begins marketing a to build a radar-blank plane. Now you\nradar-blank plane, and apparently their find that another firm begins\nplane is much faster and far more marketing a radar-blank plane, and\neconomical than yours. apparently their plane is much faster\nand far more economical than yours.\nWill you invest next $1 million to the\nradar-blank plane project? Will you invest $1 million to the radar-\nblank plane project?\nResults:\n85% of respondents said “Yes” 17% of respondents said “Yes”\nArkes, H.R., & Blumer, C. (1985). The psychology of sunk cost. Organizational Behavior and Human Decision Processes, 35(1),\n124-140. Experiment 3.\n11\n\nThe Tennessee-Tombigbee Waterway Project\n• In the Tennessee-Tombigbee Waterway Project,\nthe original cost estimate in 1970 was $323\nmillion. Difficulties were encountered during\nconstruction. The actual cost upon completion\nin 1985 were just under $2 billion, and the\nbenefit/cost ratio is far less than projected.\n• At the Congressional review on 4th Nov 1981,\nSenator Sasser mentioned: “Terminating the\n[Tennessee-Tombigbee Waterway] project at\nthis late stage of development would represent\na serious waste of funds already invested.”\nCited in Arkes, H.R., & Blumer, C. (1985). The psychology of sunk cost. Organizational Behavior and Human Decision Processes,\n35(1), 124-140.\n12\n\nGoal Substitution Effect\nGoal substitution effect: As decision makers approach project completion, they\nsubstitute a project completion goal for their original project success goal. This\ngoal substitution leads to the escalation of commitment towards the project.\n• For example: Consider a failing R&D project, although the original goal may have\nbeen profit maximization, as decision makers approach project completion, the\nnew goal may be nothing more than completing the R&D project regardless of\nfinancial returns.\n13\n\nConsider an experiment:\n• Participants were told that a R&D project is now either 10% completed (in the\n“low degree of completion” condition) or 90% completed (in the “high degree of\ncompletion” condition).\n[Note: Sunk cost was held constant across the two conditions.]\n• Participants learned about negative feedback on the R&D project, and were\nasked to allocate additional fund to the project.\n• Results: Escalation tendency is higher in the high (vs. low) degree of completion\ncondition.\nConlon, D. E., & Garland, H. (1993). The role of project completion information in resource allocation decisions. Academy of\nManagement Journal, 36(2), 402-413. Experiment 2.\n14\n\nThe 1996 Mount Everest disaster\n• The final leg of the climb is called the\nDeath Zone. Climbers need to exert\nmaximum physical effort for over 12\nhours to scale the peak and then return\nbefore a storm, avalanche, exhaustion,\nand/or oxygen deprivation strands\nthem on the mountain.\n• The summit fever:\n“I have to reach the summit this time!”\nClimbers risk everything to achieve the\ncompletion goal.\n• In 1996, some climbers failed to quit\ndespite that they knew a storm was\ncoming. They ended up staying on the\nmountain forever.\n15\n\nSelf-justification Theory\nSelf-justification theory: Negative feedback calls the validity of the prior decision\ninto question. Decision makers don’t like to think that their past decision was a\nmistake. To maintain their ego, they invest more to the failing course of action in\nhope to turn the situation around.\nThe effect of personal responsibility on escalation of commitment\nNegative feedback Negative feedback\nTime Time\nI’ve chosen a I need to justify the Someone else That wasn’t my\ncourse of action. prior decision. Let’s has chosen a mistake, I don’t\ninvest more in hope course of action. have to justify it!\nthat the situation will\nimprove.\n16\n\nConsider an experiment:\n• Participants were told to act as the Financial Vice President of a company that\nhas two divisions: Consumer Products and Industrial Products.\nHigh responsibility condition Low responsibility condition\n 1st decision: Select which  Learned that a preceding\ndivision to receive R&D financial officer has allocated\nfunding. R&D funding to a division.\n Learned that the selected  Learned that the funded\ndivision has performed poorly. division has performed poorly.\n 2nd decision: Allocate  Decision: Allocate additional\nadditional $20 million among $20 million among the two\nthe two divisions. divisions.\n• Results: Participants allocated more $$ to the previously funded division when\nthey were responsible (vs. not responsible) for the previous decision.\nStaw, B.M. (1976). Knee-deep in the big muddy: A study of escalating commitment to a chosen course of action. Organizational\nBehavior and Human Performance, 16, 27-44.\n17\n\nSelf-presentation Theory\nAccording to self-presentation theory, people are motivated to strategically\nmanage the impressions others have of them (those others could include\nsupervisors, coworkers, followers, etc.).\nIn escalation situations, decision makers want to avoid any public embarrassment\nin being associated with a failed project. Moreover, because of the social norm\nthat values decision consistency, people try to be seen as good decision makers by\npersisting with their original choice.\nno brainer\nSource of picture: https://dilbert.com/strip/1998-10-20 18\n\nSocial norm that encourages decision consistency\n“A President must, plainly, show himself to be a man made confident by the\ncourage of his own clear convictions. … The American people find it easy to\nforgive a leader's great mistakes, but not long meanderings.”\n--- Fortune Magazine (1978), in an article criticizing President Jimmy Carter\nA study has shown that leaders who are consistent in their actions\nare perceived to be better leaders than those who switch from one\nline of behavior to another.\nIn order to be seen as effective leaders, decision makers exhibit the\nescalation of commitment.\nStaw, B.M., & Ross, J. (1980). Commitment in an experimenting society: A study of the attribution of leadership from administrative\nscenarios. Journal of Applied Psychology, 65(3), 249-260.\n19\n\nPsychological Ownership and Confirmation Bias\n• Psychological ownership: Decision makers may develop psychological ownership\nwith a chosen course of action, experience a need to cultivate and protect the\nchosen course of action.\nPsychological ownership can be developed even without personal responsibility\ndue to the psychological connection among individuals.\n• Confirmation bias: With an aim to protect the chosen course of action (due to\npsychological ownership), decision makers are likely to notice evidence that\nsupports the prior decision, and ignore negative feedback.\nBeing unaware of the negative feedback, decision makers persist with the prior\ndecision.\n20\n\nThe case of Kodak digital camera\nKodak Brownie camera Kodak Kodachrome Kodak invented\n(1900) color film (1935) digital camera (1975)\n• George Eastman (Kodak’s founder) aims to make photography “as convenient\nas the pencil”. In 1900, the Brownie camera brought photography within\nfinancial reach of the general public. In 1935, Kodak launched the Kodachrome\ncolor film and became the market leader in film business. In 1975, Kodak\ninvented the world’s first digital camera; but it held back from manufacturing\ndigital cameras for the mass market, for the fear of killing its film business.\n• Many Kodak employees are proud of the success of the film business, i.e.,\npsychologically connected to Kodak’s film business.\n21\n\n• In 1981, a team inside Kodak assessed the threat that would be posed by digital\ntechnology. The report concluded that:\n“The quality of prints from electronic images will not be generally acceptable\nto consumers as replacement for prints based on the science of photography\n[i.e., film].”\n“The consumer’s desire to handle, display, and distribute prints cannot be\nreplaced by electronic display devices.”\n“Electronic systems (camera and viewing input device for TV) will not be low\nenough in price to have widespread appeal.”\nThere’s a whiff of confirmation bias in these conclusions. Kodak cannot see the\nnegative feedback.\nCarroll, P. B., & Mui, C. (2008). Billion Dollar Lessons: What You Can Learn From the Most Inexcusable Business Failures of the Last\nTwenty-five Years. New York: Portfolio.\n22\n\nDEBIASING THE ESCALATION OF COMMITMENT\nDiscussion:\nSuppose you’re a bank loan officer, and you’ve authorized a loan ($1M) to a small\nbusiness 2 years ago. The repayment deadline is approaching, but the small\nbusiness has not repaid the loan yet, and it is now applying for extra loan (another\n$1M) from you.\nGiven the mechanisms of irrational escalation of commitment (e.g., sunk cost\nfallacy, self-justification and self-presentation theories, psychological ownership\nand confirmation bias), what can you / the bank do to reduce irrational\ncommitment to problem loans?\n23\n\nLet’s examine some examples of debiasing strategies:\n1. Remove initial decision makers from subsequent decisions.\n• To reduce irrational escalation, organizations could change the decision maker;\nthe new decision maker is not responsible for the failing course of action, thus\nhas a lower level of justification pressure.\n• Data collected from 132 California banks over a 9-year period showed that the\nturnover of bank managers led to reduced commitment to problem loans,\nmanifested as:\n- Increase in the provisions for loan losses ($$ set aside in anticipation of\nuncollectible loans)\n- Increase in the write-off of bad loans (considered loans as uncollectible)\nStaw, B.M., Barsade, S.G., & Koput, K.W. (1997). Escalation at the credit window: A longitudinal study of bank executives'\nrecognition and write-off of problem loans. Journal of Applied Psychology, 82(1), 130-142.\n24\n\n2. Use self-distancing (i.e., to take the perspective of a neutral observer).\n• To reduce irrational escalation, decision makers could do\nself-distancing and adopt an observer's perspective – in\ntheir mental image they should see themselves as part of\nthe field of view.\nBy taking an observer's perspective, decision makers\ndisregard the emotional attachment to the past, engage\nin more balanced reasoning.\n• Example: Intel abandoned a once-promising line of business – memory chips:\nIntel’s business had been built on memory chips. The business was\nprofitable until Japanese competitors came into market. In 1978, Intel\nexperienced a steep decline in its market share for memory. In 1981, IBM\nselected Intel’s microprocessor to power the IBM personal computers.\n25\n\nDuring early 1980s, Intel became a company with two products: memory (which is\nunder threat) and microprocessor (which seems to have opportunity to grow).\nThere was a debate about resource allocation among these two businesses.\nIn 1985, after months of fruitless debate, Andy Grove (President of Intel) had an\ninsight during a meeting with Gordon Moore (CEO) …\nI looked out the window at the Ferris Wheel of Great America amusement park\nrevolving in the distance, then I turned back to Gordon and I asked, “if we got kicked\nout and the board brought in a new CEO, what do you think he would do?” Gordon\nanswered without hesitation, “He would get us out of memories.”\nI stared at him, numb, then said, “Why shouldn’t you and I walk out the door, come\nback in, and do it ourselves?”\nUsing self-distancing, executives at Intel prevented irrational escalation, exited its\noriginal memory business to concentrate on microprocessors.\nGrove, A. S. (1996). Only the Paranoid Survive. New York: Currency Doubleday.\n26\n\nIntended Learning Outcomes For Unit 2.7 Time For Reflection\nRecall an experience in which\nBy now, you should be able to:\nyou’ve exhibited irrational\n• Define the escalation of commitment, and discuss its\nescalation of commitment.\nimpacts in organizational context and in your\nHow would you prevent it from\npersonal life.\nhappening again in the future?\n• Describe the mechanisms underlying the escalation\nof commitment, and then suggest ways to debias.\n27",
